ind, Watts (1915–1973) provided intellectual and spiritual alternatives that helped shape the Beat culture of the 1950s and the counterculture of the 1960s. Well known for introducing Buddhist and Daoist spirituality to a wide Western audience, he also wrote on psychology, mysticism, and psychedelic experience. Many idolized Watts as a guru-mystic, yet he was also dismissed as intellectually shallow and as a mere popularizer of Asian religions (the "Norman Vincent Peale of Zen"). Both critical and appreciative, this edited volume locates Watts at the forefront of major paradigmatic shifts in Western intellectual life. Contributors explore how Watts's work resonates in present-day scholarship on psychospiritual transformation, Buddhism and psychotherapy, Daoism in the West, phenomenology and hermeneutics, humanistic and transpersonal psychology, mysticism, and ecofeminism, among other areas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aWatts, Alan,-1915-1973. 4aPsychology : Psychology. 4aPsychology : Transpersonal Psychology. 4aReligion and Spirituality : American Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Buddhism. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aRELIGION / Eastern.2bisacsh1 aBrannigan, Michael C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColumbus, Peter J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColumbus, Peter J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHood Jr., Ralph W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuang, Chungliang Al, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeightley, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrippner, Stanley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevering, Miriam L., econtributor.